Kitui Governor Julius Malombe wants the national government to set up a permanent GSU camp on the Kitui-Tana River border to end banditry.He made the demand as he condoled the families of three people shot dead during the Christmas festivities. &ldquo;I wish to convey my condolences to the bereaved families in Ukasi and Ngomeni wards,&rdquo; Malombe said in a statement.He said his administration will work with other agencies to assist the families bury their kin. About 500 families have fled their homes following the attacks. Some have sought refuge in Kathungu and Soma towns in Ukasi.The county chief said the national government is obliged to protect the lives and property of Kenyans and it should, for once, act decisively and come up with a lasting solution to the perennial problem.